IoT-based Trifluroacetic Acid (TFA) Neutralizing System;
Team Members: Aditya Sharma, Hiral Arora, Sarthak Gupta;
Core Problem Statement:
No exhaust systems in laboratories exist for real-time detection and neutralization of harmful volatile acid vapours like Trifluoroacetic Acid (TFA);
Chemical industries and pharmaceutical companies are responsible for generating large amounts of chemical waste, thus, greatly changing the acidity and alkalinity of nearby environment.
We have addressed this critical environment and laboratory safty issue issue caused by the release of harmful fluorinated by-products, particularly TFA.
TFA is a persistent, non-degradable acid that poses serious risks when released untreated into the atmosphere, especially through laboratory fume hoods. 
Current laboratory exhaust systems lack mechanisms for real-time detection and neutralization of hazardous volatile acids like TFA. Existing solutions such as wet scrubbers and solid sorbents are inefficient due to high consumption of chemicals and frequent maintainance with non selective treatment of gases.
This project proposes an intelligent IoT-enabled system that detects TFA in real-time using acidochromism (fluorescence change) in a specialized pyridocoumarin-based strip and activates a neutralization mechanism that sprays triethylamine (TEA) to neutralize TFA.
This system offers a sustainable, intelligent, and cost-effective solution to mitigate environmental and health hazards caused by TFA emissions. By combining IoT with chemical sensing and automation, it significantly improves laboratory safety and environmental protection.
